{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84370c46-27a8-4c8b-8cdb-2df9a94a4626","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides were removed. Lifecycle is now managed through the **`Window`** class.\n\n**Mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |\n\n**Approach:** Create a custom `Window` subclass and override the methods:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* was OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* was OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* was OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        return new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n    }\n}\n```\n\nMAUI also adds `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, `OnBackgrounding()`, and `OnDestroying()` for more granular control than Xamarin offered.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ce07bdb-f0f2-448f-b4a1-fb99aa7746bc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You now use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to window events.\n\nSpecifically, in MAUI:\n\n\n- The `Window` class exposes lifecycle events like `Created`, `Resumed`, `Stopped`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding` that map to the old Xamarin.Forms lifecycle methods. You can override `CreateWindow` in your `Application` class to subscribe to these window events and handle the lifecycle transitions. The `Window` class provides the modern lifecycle hooks in MAUI—`Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying`—which map to the old `Application` methods, so I'd create a custom `Window` subclass and override those methods or subscribe to the events directly.","outputTokens":1017,"requestId":"7FC9:3950:5EF73D1:67D6154:69F15760"},"id":"58ba0e53-9dca-456a-b8f1-07c03b7c2e29","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:57:23.130Z","parentId":"ef233c2f-fbb3-4374-9240-0c3fafb9cedb"}
